The '''Eastern Nazarene College''' (or '''ENC''') is a [[Private university#United States|private]], [[Mixed-sex education|coeducational]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|college of the liberal arts and sciences]] in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]] near [[Boston]], in the [[New England]] region of the [[United States]]. Known for its strong [[Religion|religious]] affiliation, distinctive [[liberal arts]] [[core curriculum]], and excellence in [[science and religion]] education. Its academic programs are primarily [[undergraduate]], with some [[professional]] [[Postgraduate|graduate]] education offered. The [[Residence hall|residential]] [[campus]], in [[Wollaston Park]] near [[Quincy Bay]], is served by the [[Wollaston (MBTA station)|Wollaston MBTA station]], and was once the summer home of [[Boston]] [[mayor]] [[Josiah Quincy, Jr.]] Established as a [[Holiness Movement|holiness]] college in [[Saratoga Springs, New York]] in 1900, it was relocated to [[Massachusetts]] in 1919.

==History==
===New York===

[[Image:Lapham.jpg|thumb|left|Pentecostal Collegiate Institute at the Rhode Island campus, c. 1905]]

On September 25, 1900, several [[come-outer]] [[Methodist Episcopal Church|Methodist]] [[clergy]] and [[laity|laymen]] affiliated with the 19th century [[Holiness movement]] opened a [[co-educational]] [[collegiate institute]] at the Garden View House in [[Saratoga Springs, New York]].<ref name="Cameron 17">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 17 }}</ref> In a time when ''pentecostal'' did not hold the same meaning as it does [[Pentecostalism|today]], but rather served as a synonym for ''[[Sacred#Holiness_in_Christianity|holiness]]'',<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Birth of a Church
  | work = 
  | publisher = Church of the Nazarene
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.usamission.org/Portals/1/Documents/Birth%20of%20a%20Church2%20(1).pdf
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = History of the Church of the Nazarene
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.nazarene.org/ministries/administration/archives/history/turn/display.aspx
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> it was named the [[Pentecostal Collegiate Institute]] (PCI) and established for the purpose of providing [[liberal education]] and [[Christian ministry|ministry]] training in a [[College preparatory|preparatory]] [[academy]], four-year [[College#United_States|college]], and [[Theology|theological]] [[seminary]].<ref name="20-21">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 20<U+2013>21
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}
</ref> PCI operated under the auspices of the Association of Pentecostal Churches of America (APCA), a [[Congregationalist polity|loose association]] of [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan]]-holiness churches<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 27
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}</ref> from eastern [[Canada]] down to the [[Middle Atlantic]], and its own [[board of education]],<ref name="ingersol">{{cite journal
  | first = Stan
  | last =  Ingersol
  | author = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Why These Schools? Historical Perspectives on Nazarene Higher Education
  | version = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://media.premierstudios.com/nazarene/docs/Why%20These%20Schools%20%20Historical%20Perspectives%20on%20Nazarene%20Higher%20Education.pdf
  | format = [[PDF]]
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> with [[Lyman C. Pettit]] as its first president. PCI was also accredited by the [[New York State Education Department]]'s [[Board of Regents]] of the [[University of the State of New York]]<ref name="called">{{cite book
  | last = Smith
  | first = Timothy L.
  | authorlink = Timothy L. Smith
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Called Unto Holiness
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1962
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = http://wesley.nnu.edu/wesleyctr/books/2501-2600/HDM2593.PDF
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = }}</ref> and was given state funding because a public school did not exist there at the time.<ref name="20-21"/> In 1901, the institute changed locations in Saratoga Springs, from the Garden View House to the former Kenmore Hotel.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Saratoga Hotel Sold
  | work = 
  | pages = 
