  | accessdate = 2008-07-10
| format=PDF}}</ref>

===Rhode Island===
The initial plans for a [[liberal arts college]] were delayed, however.<ref name="ingersol"/><ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 28<U+2013>29, 33
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}</ref> There was a falling out between Pettit and the APCA, and the school re-opened on September 16, 1902, in [[North Scituate, Rhode Island]],<ref>{{cite book
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = ''Scituate, Rhode Island''
  | publisher = Arcadia Publishing
  | year = 1998
  | location = 
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=Qyo1ui9T_gMC&printsec=frontcover
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = 0738564192
  | page = 127}}</ref> without a [[post-secondary]] curriculum.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 33<U+2013>36
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}</ref> Having been the originator of the idea for establishing PCI and having already surveyed the Rhode Island location,<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | pages = 32<U+2013>33}}</ref> [[Fred A. Hillery]] had purchased the North Scituate campus on behalf of the association.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 34 }} Originally "built and equipped for $78,000," Hillery bought it for $4,500 and negotiated a mortgage for $3,000.</ref> Its [[Greek Revival]] buildings were originally designed for the [[Smithville Seminary]] in 1839 by [[Russell Warren (architect)|Russell Warren]], the leading Greek Revival architect in [[New England]] in the 19th century,<ref>{{cite book
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
