  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =9780471143451
  | page = 422 }}</ref> but had been unused since the Lapham Institute closed in 1876. Attendance became multi-denominational after the move, only one-quarter to one-third of the student body being affiliated with the school's supporting denomination during any given academic year.<ref name="Multidenominational">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | pages = 46, 53, 61, 175}}</ref> In 1907, the APCA merged with the [[Church of the Nazarene]],<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 52 }}</ref> and PCI became one of the first three schools chosen to be officially affiliated with the Nazarenes in 1908.<ref name="hunt">{{cite book
  | last = Raser
  | first = Harold E.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = Thomas C. Hunt, James C. Carper, eds.
  | title = Religious Higher Education in the United States
