In 1917, it was decided to re-establish the liberal arts college,<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | pages = 125<U+2013>126}}</ref> and on June 14, 1918, the Eastern Nazarene College was chartered with [[academic degree|degree]]-granting authority in the state of [[Rhode Island]],<ref name="130-1">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 130}}</ref><ref name="137-1">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 137}}</ref> while [[secondary education]] would remain as the Eastern Nazarene Academy.<ref name="academy">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = The Spirit Makes the Difference: The History of Eastern Nazarene College, Part II, 1950-2000
  | publisher = ENC Press
  | year = 2000
  | location = Quincy, Massachusetts
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 57}}</ref> Choosing a new name, however, would be difficult: the school was now a liberal arts college and a Nazarene institution. Candidates included: "Northeastern Nazarene College", "[[Bresee]] Memorial College", "Nazarene College of the [[Northeastern United States|Northeast]]", and "Nazarene College and Bresee Theological Institute". [[General Superintendent (Church of the Nazarene)|General Superintendent]] [[John W. Goodwin]] can be credited with the chosen name, as he wrote to [[Hiram F. Reynolds]], also a general superintendent and a long-time supporter of the school: "I know you will do your best for our New England College. I should be glad if they would change the name to the Eastern Nazarene College, or something like that. It would seem we must have a school there, although it moves along hard and slow."<ref name="130-1"/>

===Massachusetts===
In 1919, the college moved to its current location in the [[Wollaston (Quincy, Massachusetts)|Wollaston Park]] area of [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]. The founders wanted the new college to be located near either [[Harvard]] or [[Yale]], for its graduates to attend [[graduate school]] at one or the other; Quincy won out over [[New Haven, Connecticut]] because the educational standards were known to be higher in [[Massachusetts]]<ref name="mass">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 146<U+2013>147
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}</ref> and because president-elect [[Fred J. Shields]] would only accept the position if the college were to be located near Boston.<ref name="munro">{{cite book
  | last = Munro
  | first = Bertha
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = The Years Teach, an Autobiography: Remembrances to Bless
  | publisher = Beacon Hill Press
  | year = 1970
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 
  | url = http://wesley.nnu.edu/wesleyctr/books/3401-3500/HDM3426.pdf
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}</ref> At the time of its purchase, the {{convert|12|acre|m2|sing=on}} property consisted of the [[Josiah Quincy Mansion]] (1848), built by [[Josiah Quincy, Jr.]]<ref name="pepe">{{cite book
  | last = Pepe
  | first = William J.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = Elaine A. Pepe
  | title = Postcard History Series: Quincy
  | publisher = Arcadia Publishing
  | year = 2008
  | location = 
  | pages = 72
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=NBQrnXx79-UC&printsec=frontcover#PPA72,M1
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =9780738555393 }}</ref> where Angell Hall now stands, a classroom building called the Manchester (1896), the stables (1848) on the site where Memorial Hall was built in 1948, and the Canterbury (1901), which is now Canterbury Hall. From the captain's walk of the mansion, [[Wollaston Bay]] was clearly visible down to the "ships entering and leaving the port of Boston."<ref name="147-1">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 147}}</ref> The former Rhode Island campus was purchased in 1920 by William S. Holland, who moved his [[Watchman Institute]] there in 1923.

