The trustees of the college were incorporated by the state in 1920,<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Hood
  | first = William Ross
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = State Laws Relating to Education Enacted in 1920 and 1921
  | publisher = Department of the Interior: Bureau of Education
  | year = 1922
  | location = District of Columbia
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=snQaAAAAYAAJ
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 224 }}</ref> by which time its [[liberal arts]] identity had been "quite firmly established,"<ref name="hunt"/> but it took another decade to gain [[bachelor of arts]] degree-granting power from the commonwealth.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 163 }} Before 1930, an arrangement was made with [[Northwest Nazarene College]] for students to receive degrees from that institution instead.</ref> President [[Floyd W. Nease]] appealed directly to the [[General Court of Massachusetts]], and defended his petition before the Joint Committee on Education and the House and Senate on January 28, 1930, calling on financial records, campus improvement plans, and prominent community leaders; the bill passed in both houses and was signed by Governor [[Frank G. Allen]] on March 12, 1930.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | pages = 194<U+2013>195
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn = }}</ref> The news reached the college the following afternoon.<ref name="allen">{{cite news 
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Gov. Allen Signs Nazarene College Degree Grant Bill
  | work = [[The Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = March 14, 1930
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref> The next year under President [[R. Wayne Gardner]], the [[trustee]]s made a statement reaffirming that the college would remain "distinctly [[interdenominational]] and cosmopolitan in service."<ref name="interdenominational">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
