  | isbn =
  | page = 330}}</ref>

[[Image:gatesealENC.jpg|thumb|left|College seal on the main campus gate, a gift of the class of 1938]]

Under President [[Gideon B. Williamson]] on December 3, 1943, the Eastern Nazarene College gained [[Educational accreditation|accreditation]] from the [[New England Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]],<ref name="1943-44">{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 293}}</ref> and became the second Nazarene college to ever gain institutional accreditation.<ref name="vol2">{{cite book
  | last = Purkiser
  | first = Westlake Taylor
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Called Unto Holiness, Vol. 2
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1983
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = http://wesley.nnu.edu/wesleyctr/books/2601-2700/HDM2623.PDF
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = }} The first was the [[Northwest Nazarene College]] in [[Idaho]], which was accredited as a four-year school in 1937, while ENC alumnus [[Russell V. DeLong]] was president there.</ref> ENC was also admitted to the [[Association of American Colleges]] in 1944,<ref name="1943-44"/> and an affiliation with [[Quincy City Hospital]] for nurses' training began in that same year.<ref name="coop"/> Eastern Nazarene was soon dubbed "Our Quincy's College" by the Quincy ''[[Patriot Ledger]]''<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Our Quincy's College
  | work = 
  | pages = 1, 4
