  | date = October 5, 1948
  | url = 
  | accessdate = }}</ref> and has since maintained good [[town and gown]] relations with the city.<ref name="neighbors">{{cite news 
  | last =
  | first = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Editorial: Quincy home to more collegians
  | work = [[Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = August 23, 1996
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref> The Eastern Nazarene Academy would close after 1955,<ref name="academy"/> and starting in 1956, professors [[Timothy L. Smith]] and [[Charles W. Akers]] began to establish a [[community college]] for the city of Quincy.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = History Department
  | work = 
  | publisher = Eastern Nazarene College
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/history/dept_hist.html
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = August 4, 2009}}</ref> In 1964, the graduate course in theology was discontinued and replaced with a [[master's degree]] program in religion.<ref name="Balmer">{{cite book
  | last = Balmer
  | first = Randall Herbert
  | authorlink = Randall Herbert Balmer
