==Campus==
===Wollaston Park===

[[Image:Babcockarboretumtree.jpg|thumb|right|The college campus is also home to the Babcock Arboretum.]]

The {{convert|21|acre|m2|sing=on}} main campus<ref>{{cite map
|publisher =
|title = Campus map
|url = http://www1.enc.edu/About-ENC/Campus-Map.aspx
|edition =
|section =
|accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> of the Eastern Nazarene College is situated in the [[Wollaston Park]] neighborhood of [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]. The Wollaston Park campus is roughly {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} southeast from the [[Boston]] [[Neponset River|city line]] and {{convert|6|mi|km}} south of [[Government Center, Boston|downtown Boston]],<ref name="about">{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College: About
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/about/index.htm
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> just over {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of [[Quincy Center]], {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} northeast of the [[Wollaston (MBTA station)|Wollaston T station]],<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Wollaston MBTA Station (with Google map)
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/subway/lines/stations/?stopId=15412
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> and {{convert|0.25|mi|km}} southwest from [[Wollaston Beach]]. ENC purchased the Wollaston Park property, then a {{convert|12|acre|m2|sing=on}} parcel, from the former Quincy Mansion School for Girls for $50,000 in 1919,<ref name="mass"/> and has added to it over the years. The [[Mount Wollaston]] land belonging to the [[Quincy family]] had been broken up into prestigious building lots and named Wollaston Park during in the late 19th century, to become one of Boston's first [[commuter]] neighborhoods,<ref name="Babcock">Information provided by the Eastern Nazarene College, [http://books.google.com/books?id=IdoCHAAACAAJ History of the Babcock Arboretum, published in 2003, written by Gerry Wood], founder. Found in the Nease Library, Reference Section.</ref> and the area remains primarily [[Residential area|residential]]. The campus is also a registered [[arboretum]], named the Babcock Arboretum after Vernor J. Babcock and dedicated in 1993.<ref name="Babcock"/> The ''[[alma mater]]'', set to the tune of "[[Annie Lisle]]" with lyrics written by former president Edward S. Mann, not only refers to Quincy Bay but also the existence of the [[elm]] trees for which Elm Avenue was named,<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Alumni Relations at Eastern Nazarene College
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/IA/alumni_relations.php
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-12-30}}</ref> all of which died with the onset of [[Dutch elm disease]] in the early to mid-20th century. The college has historically maintained good [[town and gown]] relations with the Quincy community,<ref name="neighbors"/> and the campus has been home to the Anglican Parish of Saint George, established by the Anglican Mission in America, since 2009.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = New Anglican Church
  | work = [[The Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = February 28, 2009
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref>

The [[Quincy Mansion]] (1848) purchased by the college in 1919 was demolished in 1969. Its [[chandelier]]s were sold for food during the [[Great Depression]].<ref name="munro"/> It was once part of the Quincy family homestead along with the [[Dorothy Quincy House]] and the [[Josiah Quincy House]], on a {{convert|200|acre|km2|sing=on}} parcel of land known as the "Lower Farm". The mansion itself was situated on the land where Angell Hall now stands, and was the summer home of [[Josiah Quincy, Jr.]], then mayor of Boston. It was three stories and white, in [[Georgian architecture]], with marble fireplaces in most of the rooms and large [[French window]]s on the first floor that "opened upon either little balconies or broad [[piazza]]s."<ref name="147-1"/> Elm Avenue had been the avenue, or driveway, for the two mansions on the property.<ref name="Babcock"/> The first of the two, the Josiah Quincy House (1770), still stands on Muirhead Street.

[[Image:GardnerHallENC.JPG|thumb|right|Gardner Hall (1930), the main college administration building]]

Both Gardner Hall (1930), originally named the Fowler Memorial Administration Building after [[Charles J. Fowler]], and the original Floyd W. Nease Library (1953), now the Bower-Grimshaw Center for Institutional Advancement, were designed by Wesley Angell. Gardner Hall was designed in the [[Classical architecture|Classical]] or [[Colonial Revival architecture|Colonial Revival]] mode. Gardner is brick, three stories on a high granite basement, and capped by a [[parapet]] [[balustrade]]d in the center. Corners are articulated with brick [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]]. The fenestration is symmetric with double sash windows at regular intervals, trimmed in white, topped with flared brick [[lintel]]s and a white [[keystone (architecture)|keystone]]. It also features a two-story balustraded [[Doric order|Doric]] [[portico]] of fluted cast stone [[column]]s. The portico is the backdrop for [[commencement speech|commencement]] ceremonies. The main entrance, at the end of wide stairs, is pilastered and topped with a bracketed entablature, which frames an arched glass opening. The side elevations have projecting stair towers, which indicate the site of a central hall running the length of the building. Originally rectangular in form, the 1953 addition of the then-Nease Library in the rear bestowed upon it a T-configuration.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Historical and architectural significance of the campus of Eastern Nazarene College
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://thomascranelibrary.org/htm/503.htm
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref>

[[File:Memorial Hall, Eastern Nazarene College(2).jpg|thumb|left|Memorial Hall (1948), for those who served and died in World War II]]

Memorial Hall (1948) holds the distinction of the only building on campus, other than the pre-existing Canterbury Hall (1901), not to be named for any one individual. Rather, it was built as a memorial to those who had served in the [[Second World War]]. Over two hundred alumni had served, and six students had given their lives.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = The Spirit Makes the Difference: The History of Eastern Nazarene College, Part II, 1950-2000
  | publisher = ENC Press
  | year = 2000
  | location = Quincy, Massachusetts
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 11 }}</ref>

===Old Colony and other locations===
The {{convert|6|acre|m2|sing=on}} Old Colony Campus (OCC), named for its location on Old Colony Avenue in Quincy, has two buildings. The 180 building is the Adams Executive Center, which houses the business department in the Cecil R. Paul Center for Business, established in 1999.<ref name="occ"/> The building at 162 Old Colony houses the college archives and offices for the history department as part of the James R. Cameron Center for History, Law, and Government, established in 2005, as well as separate offices for mathematics, and physics and engineering departments, and the Campus Kinder Haus (CKH), an early childhood education center.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Photo tour: Campus Kinder Haus
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www1.enc.edu/subpage.aspx?id=1009
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-01-03}}</ref> CKH was founded in 1979 and moved to the Old Colony Campus in 2000.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Davis
  | first = Joy
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Kinder Haus finally at home
  | work = [[The Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = September 26, 2000
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref> The college also owns adjacent undeveloped land between Old Colony and Hancock Street in Quincy, at the Southern Artery,<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =
  | first =
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Rezoning of parcel debated; Property value would drop, says Eastern Nazarene
  | work = [[Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = September 24, 2002
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref> that has been rezoned by the city several times,<ref>{{cite news 
  | last =
  | first =
  | coauthors = 
  | title = City council rezones college land; Officials at ENC opposed the move
  | work = [[Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = October 9, 2002
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref> and Quincy officials announced in 2009 they might take it by [[eminent domain]] for the construction of a new [[middle school]].<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Encarnacao
  | first = Jack
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Quincy looking to take inn, other properties to create site for new middle school
  | work = [[Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = PatriotLedger.com
  | date = July 9, 2009
  | url = http://www.patriotledger.com/news/education/x1885888099/Quincy-looking-to-take-inn-other-properties-to-create-site-for-new-middle-school
  | accessdate = July 23, 2009}}</ref>

In addition to its campuses in Quincy, the college established a learning annex called the Auburn Learning Center in [[Auburn, Massachusetts]] in 1997 to function as part of the Leadership Education for Adults Division,<ref name="auburn"/> and added satellite campuses in [[Boston]], [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton]], [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]], and [[Swansea, Massachusetts|Swansea]], [[Massachusetts]] in 2008.<ref name="satellite"/><ref name="extending"/>

==Organization==

[[Image:Wollastonsteeple.jpg|thumb|right|The Wollaston Church of the Nazarene seen from the college campus in Wollaston Park]]

===Religious affiliation===
[[Higher education]] is, historically, one of the Nazarenes' most important emphases, and the Nazarenes provide their colleges with "students, administrative and faculty leadership, and financial and spiritual support.... the college, while not a local congregation, is an integral part of the church; it is an expression of the church."<ref>{{cite book
  | last =
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Manual of the History, Doctrine, Government, and Ritual of the Church of the Nazarene
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 2005
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = http://media.premierstudios.com/nazarene/docs/Manual2005_09.pdf
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 170}}</ref> Originally founded under the auspices of the [[Association of Pentecostal Churches of America]], ENC was one of the first three schools officially chosen to be [[Church of the Nazarene#Higher education|Nazarene institution]] in 1915,<ref name="hunt"/> making it the oldest continuously operating educational institution affiliated with the Nazarenes. As one of eight Nazarene [[liberal arts college]]s<ref>{{cite journal
  | first = Price
  | last = J. Matthew 
  | author = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Liberal Arts and the Priorities of Nazarene Higher Education
  | version = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://media.premierstudios.com/nazarene/docs/didache_2_1_Price.pdf
  | format = [[PDF]]
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}} Nazarene [[higher education]] is based on the [[liberal arts college]] model. While ENC is the only Nazarene institution to retain the "college" moniker, no Nazarene schools fit the [http://educationusa.ecacms.getusinfo.com/home/education-usa/global-left-nav/graduate-study/about-graduate-education-in-the-u/types-of-institutions standard national definition] of a "research university". Furthermore, the [[Commonwealth of Massachusetts]] [http://www.mass.edu/home.asp Board of Higher Education] holds a "[http://www.mass.edu/forinstitutions/academic/documents/610CMR.pdf two doctorate]" standard.</ref> in the United States,<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = US Educational Regions
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.nazarene.org/files/docs/educregions.pdf
  |format=PDF| doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}} ENC and [[Northwest Nazarene University|NNU]] are the only Nazarene schools to remain true to their regional names.</ref> the college receives financial backing equivalent to a $40 million [[Financial endowment|endowment]] from its constituent churches.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Jaschik
  | first = Scott
  | coauthors = Kate Maternowski
  | title = Show me the money
  | work = 
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = ''[[Inside Higher Ed]]''
  | date = May 11, 2009
  | url = http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2009/05/11/enroll
  | accessdate = 2009-05-13}}</ref> Eastern Nazarene is also bound by a [[gentlemen's agreement]] not to actively recruit outside its respective [[Church of the Nazarene#Organization|educational region]],<ref>{{cite book
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Guidelines and Handbook for Educational Institutions of the Church of the Nazarene
  | publisher = Church of the Nazarene International Board of Education
  | year = 1997
  | location = 
  | url = http://www.nazarene.org/files/docs/guide.pdf
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 14}}</ref> which extends southwest from [[Maine]] as far as [[Pennsylvania]] and [[Virginia]] in the United States<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern USA Region
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.nazarene.org/files/docs/EasternUSAregiondistricts.pdf 
  |format=PDF| doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref><ref>When first established on June 10, 1918, this region also included Ohio, West Virginia, maritime Canada, and the British Isles. {{cite book
  | last =
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Manual of the History, Doctrine, Government, and Ritual of the Church of the Nazarene
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1919
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = http://www.mnu.edu/academics/mabee/manuals/Pentecostal_Church_of_the_Nazarene_1919.pdf
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = }}</ref> and provides [[trustee]]s for the college.<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 131 }}</ref> The institution is otherwise largely independent, having been multi-denominational since 1902,<ref name="Multidenominational"/> and [[tuition]]-driven, with an actual endowment of only [[United States dollar|US $]]11,015,937.<ref name="usnews"/> The president and trustees of the college determined in 1931, one year after gaining its charter to grant degrees in Massachusetts, that it is part of the college's mission to be "distinctly [[interdenominational]] and cosmopolitan in service."<ref name="interdenominational"/> Students are not required to profess any [[religion]], but faculty members are required to be Christians.<ref name="faith">{{cite news 
  | last = Davis
  | first = Joy
  | coauthors = 
