==Academics==

[[Image:MunrohallENC.jpg|thumb|right|Munro Hall (1926), the first building erected by the college in Massachusetts]]

According to some of the college's earliest and most influential figures, the Eastern Nazarene College has always existed with the idea in mind that one can be a Christian and an [[intellectual]] [[scholar]]: Bertha Munro, the first [[Dean (education)|dean]] of the college and a [[Boston University]], [[Radcliffe College|Radcliffe]], and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] [[alumna]], is often quoted as having said that "there is no conflict between the best in education and the best in Christian faith"<ref>{{cite book
  | last = Cameron
  | first = James R.
  | authorlink = James R. Cameron
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College<U+2014>The First Fifty Years, 1900-1950
  | publisher = Nazarene Publishing House
  | year = 1968
  | location = Kansas City
  | url = 
  | doi = 
  | id = 
  | isbn =
  | page = 317 }}</ref> and former history professor [[Timothy L. Smith]], a [[University of Virginia]] and Harvard [[alumnus]] who began his career at ENC, is widely considered the first [[evangelical Christian]] to gain academic prominence,<ref name="ct">{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Historian Smith, 72, Dies
  | work = Obituaries
  | publisher = Christianity Today
  | date = 4/07/1997 12:00AM
  | url = http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/1997/april7/1997-04-07-obituary-historian-smith-72-dies.html
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> while ENC alumnus and physicist [[Karl Giberson]] has worked to address the [[Creation-Evolution controversy]] and was Executive Vice President of the [[BioLogos Foundation]] until May, 2011.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Karl Giberson Moves On to Create More Time for Writing
  | work = The BioLogos Forum
  | publisher = BioLogos.org
  | date = 
  | url = http://biologos.org/blog/karl-giberson-moves-on-to-create-more-time-for-writing
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2011-10-25}}</ref> Though it makes no religious requirements of its students, Eastern Nazarene has required that its faculty members be Christian since 1993.<ref name="faith"/> The school currently has three college divisions: the Traditional Undergraduate Division, the Adult Studies Division (often called the Leadership Education for Adults Division, or LEAD), and the Graduate Division.<ref name="catalogue">{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College 2008-2009 Undergraduate Catalog
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/downloads/undergraduate_catalogs/undergraduate_catalog_08-09.pdf
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-03-08}}</ref> There were 1,075 students enrolled at the college in 2007, 927 of whom were [[undergraduate]] and 148 of whom were [[graduate student]]s.<ref name="nces">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/globallocator/|title=Search for Schools, Colleges, and Libraries|publisher=U.S. Department of Education National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=2009-04-14}}</ref> Admission is selective<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College
  | work = Carnegie Classification
  | publisher = Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.carnegiefoundation.org/classifications/sub.asp?key=748&subkey=14645&start=783
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref> on a [[Rolling admission|rolling deadline]] and the 2007 acceptance rate for students who applied to the college was 61.7 percent.<ref name="usnews">{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College
  | work = Guide to Best Colleges
  | publisher = U.S. News and World Report
  | date = 
  | url = http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/college/items/2145
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-05-19}}</ref>

===Traditional Undergraduate Division===
Most degree offerings at Eastern Nazarene are [[Bachelor's|baccalaureate]] degrees. In the Traditional Undergraduate Division, the college offers [[Associate's degree|associate's]] and [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor's]] ([[bachelor of arts]] and [[bachelor of science]]) [[liberal arts]] degrees in 50 [[Academic major|major]]s, with 57 [[Academic minor|minor]]s and 6 pre-professional programs for a combined total of 80 programs of study, including [[dual degree]] programs with [[Northeastern University]] and the [[Massachusetts College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences]] leading to the [[doctor of pharmacy]].<ref name="catalogue"/> In addition to co-operative programs and internship opportunities around Boston, Eastern Nazarene provides a number of intercollegiate and off-campus programs at 56 [[Church of the Nazarene|Nazarene]] institutions of [[higher education]] around the world. Students may also participate in the "Best Semester"<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Best Semester
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.bestsemester.com/
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> study abroad program, and ENC offers an additional semester-long program in [[Romania]].<ref name="Balmer"/> The college uses a "4-1-4 system"<ref name="usnews"/> for its academic year: there are two full [[Academic term|semesters]] in the [[autumn|Fall]] and Spring, each roughly four months long, and a one-month term in January known as "J Term".

Eastern Nazarene emphasizes a blend of faith and other pursuits, from biology<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Lambert
  | first = Lane
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Making room for God and evolution; Nazarene prof says they're not mutually exclusive
  | work = 
  | pages = 1
  | language = 
  | publisher = ''[[The Patriot Ledger]]''
  | date = March 5, 2008
  | url = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> to business,<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Lambert
  | first = Lane
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Speaker preaches faith in the office; Former investment banker says companies should embrace the Lord's work
  | work = 
  | pages = 10
  | language = 
  | publisher = ''[[The Patriot Ledger]]''
  | date = November 15, 2006
  | url = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> and has won the [[John Templeton]] award for science-and-religion education.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Professors honored for science-religion course Eastern Nazarene program explores common ground
  | work = [[Patriot Ledger]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = August 24, 1996
  | url = 
  | accessdate = July 24, 2009}}</ref> The undergraduate curriculum at Eastern Nazarene was developed in 1919 by the first dean of the college, Bertha Munro, and originally modeled after the curricula at [[Radcliffe College]] and [[Boston University]].<ref name="munro"/> A revision that introduced the Cultural Perspectives core sequence is very distinctive and comprises a series of [[interdisciplinary]] courses on Western culture that encourages students to ponder the "tensions and possibilities" in the relationships between the Christian faith and societal values.<ref name="Balmer"/> The traditional undergraduate student-to-faculty ratio at Eastern Nazarene is 11:1,<ref name="usnews"/> and graduates on average have a 94 percent acceptance rate into [[medical school]] as well as a 100 percent acceptance rate into [[law school]].<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College History
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www1.enc.edu/About-ENC/History.aspx
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref>

===Graduate Division and LEAD===

[[Image:PaulcenterENC.jpg|thumb|right|College name and shield on the side of the Cecil R. Paul Center for Business at the Old Colony Campus]]

In addition to traditional undergraduate education, the college offers [[continuing education]] for working adults through the Leadership Education for Adults Division (LEAD). Accelerated programs have been in place since 1990,<ref name="caahe"/> and now include bachelor's [[degree completion]] (bachelor of arts and bachelor of science degrees) and [[associate's degree]]s (the [[associate of arts]] degree) as well as certificates in [[paralegal]] studies (CPS) and [[human resource management]] (CHRM).<ref name="adult and grad">{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Adult and Graduate Programs
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/adult_studies/programs.php
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> The college also maintains 2+2 programs<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = 2+2 BAM Programs
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www1.enc.edu/subpage.aspx?fid=110
  | format = 
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> and [[articulation (education)|articulation]] agreements with [[junior college]]s in the surrounding geographical area, like the agreements with [[Bristol Community College|Bristol]], [[Massasoit Community College|Massasoit]], and [[Roxbury Community College]]s.<ref name="satellite"/><ref name="extending"/> Most LEAD classes are held at the Old Colony Campus or at one of the four [[satellite campus]]es for reasons of transportation and accessibility, such as parking space, which is limited at the main campus, and access to [[public transportation]] via the [[Wollaston (MBTA Station)|Wollaston T Station]], located on Beale Street where it intersects with Old Colony Avenue.

Current [[graduate education|graduate]] offerings from the Graduate Division are primarily [[master's degrees]] ([[master of science]] and [[master of education]]).<ref name="adult and grad"/> Eastern Nazarene first offered graduate work in theology in 1938,<ref name="degrees"/> then replaced it with a master's degree in religion in 1964, and added master's degrees in business, education, and psychology in 1981.<ref name="Balmer"/>

==Student life==

[[Image:MannStudentCenter.jpg|thumb|right|The Mann Student Center, named for Edward S. Mann]]

In 2006, students from 21 countries and 31 [[U.S. state]]s were attending Eastern Nazarene.<ref name="reg">Eastern Nazarene College, Office of the Registrar: 617-745-3877/registrar@enc.edu<!-- contact to verify and for more information --></ref> ENC is 24&nbsp;percent ethnically diverse,<ref name="best">{{cite press release
  | title = ENC Named One of "America<U+2019>s Best Colleges"
  | publisher = Eastern Nazarene College
  | date = February 5, 2007
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/news/2007/news_ranking.htm
  | accessdate = 2009-02-08}}</ref> the highest diversity rate among the eight Nazarene liberal arts colleges,<ref name="educate">{{cite news 
  | last = Johnson
  | first = Carolyn Y.
  | coauthors = 
  | title = A calling to educate: New head of Christian college aims to train 'people of value'
  | work = [[Boston Globe]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = Boston.com
  | date = July 31, 2005
  | url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2005/07/31/a_calling_to_educate/
  | accessdate = July 23, 2009}}</ref> and [[Black people|black student]] enrollment rose from 4.9 to 15&nbsp;percent between 1997 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Redden
  | first = Elizabeth
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Christian Colleges Grow More Diverse
  | work = 
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = [[InsideHigherEd]].com
  | date = August 15, 2008
  | url = 
  | accessdate = 2009-02-08}}</ref> Eastern Nazarene has always been [[co-educational]], and most of the traditional undergraduate population lives on campus.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = ENC Student Handbook (p. 27)
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/downloads/student_handbook.pdf
  | format = [[PDF]]
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-06-11}}</ref> Undergraduate students at ENC are typically affiliated with approximately 30 different [[Christian denomination]]s (the largest representations being Nazarene, [[Baptist]], [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]], and [[Non-denominational Christianity|non-denominational]]), while 35 percent of the student population had no reported denominational or religious affiliation.<ref name="faith"/><ref name="reg"/>

No student is required to be [[Christian]] to attend the Eastern Nazarene College,<ref name="faith"/> but each traditional undergraduate student, upon registering, agrees to what is called a Lifestyle [[Covenant (law)|Covenant]]: to, among other things, "abstain from the use of illegal drugs, alcohol and tobacco, and to avoid attendance at bars, clubs, or other activities or places of entertainment that promote themes of inappropriate sexuality, violence, profanity, pornography or activities demeaning to human life."<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = Eastern Nazarene College Application for Undergraduate Admission
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/undergrad/application.htm
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> The Student Handbook also specifies that "No person shall engage in sexual acts with anyone other than a spouse."<ref>{{cite web
  | last = 
  | first = 
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = 
  | title = ENC Student Handbook (11.2, p. 51)
  | work = 
  | publisher = 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.enc.edu/downloads/student_handbook.pdf
  | format = [[PDF]]
  | doi = 
  | accessdate = 2009-06-11}}</ref> While some guidelines might appear to be "[[relic]]s from another era," according to the ''[[Boston Globe]]'',<ref name="focus">{{cite news 
  | last = Johnson
  | first = Carolyn Y.
  | coauthors = 
  | title = School's religious focus remains as rules evolve
  | work = [[Boston Globe]]
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = Boston.com
  | date = July 31, 2005
  | url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2005/07/31/schools_religious_focus_remains_as_rules_evolve/
  | accessdate = July 23, 2009}}</ref> the ''Globe'' has also noted that other prominent Christian colleges uphold these ideals,<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = MacQuarrie
  | first = Brian
  | coauthors = 
  | title = On Christian campus, an all-embracing framework: College in Illinois shows value trend
  | work = 
  | pages = 
  | language = 
  | publisher = ''[[The Boston Globe]]''
  | date = November 14, 2005
  | url = http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2005/11/14/on_christian_campus_an_all_embracing_framework/
  | accessdate = 2008-07-10}}</ref> and that Eastern Nazarene is known for being a progressive "trendsetter"<ref name="educate"/> with a "slightly more [[Social liberalism|liberal]] bent" than its peers.<ref name="focus"/> The [[John Templeton Foundation]] has also cited the Eastern Nazarene College as one that builds [[Moral character|character]],<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Jackson
  | first = Derrick Z.
  | coauthors = 
